Einstein Lookalike Segments

Use an Einstein lookalike segment to find an audience similar to an existing one. A lookalike segment is based on insights from your entire audience. You determine the seed segment and the additional characteristics and demographics for the audience outside of the seed segment. Einstein then uses data to find the right audience, ensuring that it is most similar to the seed segment. The lookalike model runs every 7 days for each seed segment.

EXAMPLE Your company sells outdoor adventure gear online. You have a customer base that frequently purchases camping equipment. However, the purchase segments are too small to meaningfully target with your budget, and targeting your entire audience doesn’t fit in your budget. You run a lookalike segment against a seed segment for your new campaign to promote hiking boots. You set the additional audience size to match your budget. Einstein finds the individuals who are most similar to the seed segment for your campaign by finding people who demonstrated an interest in outdoor activities based on their browsing and purchase history.
Create an Einstein Lookalike Segment
The segment you use to create the lookalike segment is the seed segment. Choose a seed segment on which to build your lookalike segment and define the characteristics for the additional audience size. The audience size is the number of individuals outside of the seed segment that you want in your lookalike segment. You can configure and build Einstein lookalike segments on individual objects or unified individual objects. To reach your desired audience size, Einstein first looks for extremely similar matches. Then, if the audience size isn’t reached, Einstein checks for moderately similar matches. Regardless of the audience size you choose, Einstein selects individuals who are ranked according to similarity to the seed segment.
Edit an Einstein Lookalike Segment
You can change a segment’s name, description, or publishing schedule. Due to processing differences from regular segments, you don’t see rules for Einstein lookalike segments.
Stop Running an Einstein Lookalike Segment
An Einstein Lookalike segment is based on a seed segment, and multiple lookalike segments can use the same seed segment. You can stop using a seed segment to create Einstein lookalike segments. For example, if you want to run an Einstein lookalike segment on a different seed segment, you can keep the current segment but stop the processing to save costs. Multiple lookalike segments can run on a single seed segment. In addition, if you want to delete a seed segment, you first must stop running and then delete any Einstein lookalike segments that use the seed segment.
Delete an Einstein Lookalike Segment
Delete an Einstein lookalike segment if it’s no longer needed. If an active Einstein lookalike segment is running on a seed segment, you have to first stop running the lookalike, then you can delete it. If you delete a lookalike segment, you can’t reenable it. If you want to delete a seed segment, you must first delete all the associated Einstein lookalike segments.
